With large AME (cf. 
Fig. 5A, B
; diameter 45 µm, i.e. 78 % of PME diameter). Gonopore without epiandrous spigots (
Fig. 5C
). ALS with one widened spigot, one long pointed spigot, and six cylindrical spigots (
Fig. 5E
). Cheliceral apophyses set with cuticular denticles (
Fig. 6A, B
); distance between tips of apophyses: 180 µm; stridulatory files with ~ 30 ridges (
Fig. 7A
), distances between ridges proximally 2.1 µm, distally 3.0 µm. Stridulatory pick proximally on palpal femur (
Fig. 6C
). Palpal tarsal organ exposed (
Fig. 6D
), diameter of rim ~8 µm. Sperm duct opening subdistally on bulbal process (
Fig. 6F
). Tibia 1 with sexually dimorphic short ‘vertical’ hairs in two prolateral and two retrolateral rows, without branches (
Fig. 7C, D
); putative chemoreceptors with several short side branches (cf. 
Fig. 7B
). Leg femora, tibiae, metatarsi, and tarsi (the latter only proximally) with small cuticular plates (cf. 
Fig. 7B
) in regular intervals, up to approximately six on each side (prolaterally and retrolaterally), diameter ~5 µm. Leg trichobothria feathered (
Fig. 8B
), prolateral trichobothrium on tibia 1 present. Apparently without rimmed pores on legs. Proximally ventrally on metatarsi 3 and 4 with slender hairs (cf. 
Fig. 8D, E
); diameters proximally 2–3 µm, versus 4–5 µm in neighboring mechanoreceptors; shape of hair basis similar to neighboring mechanoreceptors, but shaft similar to trichobothria; metatarsus 3 with only two such hairs, metatarsus 4 with four to five; distally very thin and long, with distinctively widened tips (cf. 
Fig. 8F
; ~0.6 µm diameter, versus 0.3 µm subdistally). Leg tarsal organs exposed (
Fig. 9A–D
), diameters of rim 5–7 µm. Tarsus 4 distally apparently with two comb hairs on prolateral side (not seen clearly). Main tarsal claws with ~10–12 teeth, claws on tarsus 4 slightly different in shape (teeth directed more towards distal) (cf. 
Fig. 7E, F
).

With relatively small AME (cf. 
Fig. 11A
; diameter 20 µm, i.e. 50 % of PME diameter). Gonopore without epiandrous spigots (
Fig. 11B
). ALS with one widened spigot, one long pointed spigot, and six cylindrical spigots (
Fig. 11C
). Stridulatory files on chelicerae with ~ 55 ridges (
Fig. 11F
), distances between ridges proximally 3.1 µm, distally 0.8 µm. Palpal tarsal organ exposed (
Fig. 12A
), diameter ~7 µm. Bulbal process consisting of two parts (
Fig. 12B, C
); one part with wide tip, prominent denticles, and subdistal sperm duct opening; other part more slender, proximally with (glandular?) pores, distally curved. Tibiae 1 and 2 with sexually dimorphic short ‘vertical’ hairs in two prolateral and two retrolateral rows, without branches (
Fig. 13A
); putative chemoreceptors with several short side branches (
Fig. 13B
). Leg femora, tibiae, metatarsi, and tarsi (the latter only proximally) with small cuticular plates (cf. 
Fig. 13C
) in regular intervals, up to approximately six on each side (prolaterally and retrolaterally), diameter ~5 µm. Leg trichobothria feathered (cf. 
Fig. 13D
). Apparently without rimmed pores on legs. Proximally ventrally on metatarsi 3 and 4 with slender hairs (
Fig. 13E
); diameters proximally 1.3–1.6 µm, versus 2.4–2.6 µm in neighboring mechanoreceptors; shape of hair basis similar to neighboring mechanoreceptors, but shaft similar to trichobothria; metatarsus 3 with only three such hairs, metatarsus 4 with approximately ten; distally with distinctively widened tips (cf. 
Fig. 13H
; ~ 1.5 µm diameter, versus 0.9 µm subdistally). Leg tarsal organs exposed (
Fig. 14E
), diameters 5–6 µm. Tarsus 4 distally apparently with two comb hairs on prolateral side (not seen clearly). Main tarsal claws with ~9–10 teeth (cf. 
Fig. 14A, B
); claws on tarsus 4 slightly different in shape (teeth directed more towards distal) (
Fig. 14C
).

Without stridulatory files on chelicerae (
Fig. 12D
). With short chemoreceptive hairs like in male but without sexually dimorphic short ‘vertical’ hairs. Epigynum without pockets (
Fig. 15A, B
), with large posterior plate; internal genitalia (
Fig. 15C–F
) with pair of pore plates of slightly variable shape (round to slightly oval) and at slightly variable distance from each other (see Variation below).

The three pairs of dark marks on the carapace are variably distinct and in some specimens even absent (
Fig. 4C–F
). The female internal genitalia are slightly variable with respect to pore plate shape, size, and distance: in one cleared female from 
type
locality oval, diameter 25 x 45 µm, distance 95 µm (
Huber & Carvalho 2019
); in two cleared females from Kueba di Brua round, diameter 30 µm, distance 120 µm (
Fig. 15D, F
).

Known from several mainland and island localities in the southeastern Caribbean (
Fig. 3
).

PALPS. As in 
Fig. 17
; coxa unmodified; trochanter with indistinct ventral protrusion; femur large and strongly widened, proximally on retrolateral side with distinct process; femur-patella joints shifted toward prolateral side (arrows in 
Fig. 17A
); patella triangular in lateral view, i.e. ventrally very short (possibly not closed); tibia with two trichobothria in relatively proximal position; tibia-tarsus joints not shifted towards one side; tarsus simple; procursus (
Fig. 18A–C
) proximal part strongly widened in lateral view, with rounded dorsal protrusion and indistinct ventral pocket (or ridge), distal part consisting of distinctive black sclerotized element and transparent membranous elements; genital bulb (
Fig. 18D–F
) with simple sclerite connecting to tarsus, main part oval, and large sclerotized process with numerous denticles on prolateral side, with sperm duct opening on dorsal side (arrow in 
Fig. 18E
).

In general very similar to male (
Fig. 16B, D, F
); legs without curved hairs, with few ‘vertical’ hairs. Cheliceral stridulatory files distinct as in male. Epigynum (
Fig. 19B–D
) main plate trapezoidal, slightly protruding, anteriorly medially whitish, posteriorly medially with low rounded process; with dark central internal structure visible in uncleared specimens; posterior plate simple, medially whitish. Internal genitalia as in 
Fig. 19E–G
, with elongated pore plates in transversal position; semitransparent ‘valve’ dorsal of large trapezoidal internal structure (arrow in 
Fig. 19F
); complex system of membranous structures medially posteriorly (
Fig. 19G
).
